c++ cast

You must know which cast to use in which condition?

• static cast
	------------
		- Does Semantic check
		- 	Not Reliable at run	//Just because it compiled, it doesn't mean it is reliable
		-	Not tested at run

		- do  CONVERSION
		- do Upcast
		- do Downcast

• dynamic cast
	---------------
		- Does Semantic check
		- Reliable at run			//unlike static cast this is reliable at run
		- Tested at run

		- do Upcast
		- do Downcast

• const cast
	------------
		- Type qualified?
		
• reinterpret cast
	-----------------
		- Do Upcast
		- Do Downcast
		- Do reinterpretation

		- There is hierarchy between types.
		- void type is more generic, whereas, float type is accurate.
		- Parent class is more generic, whereas Child class is accurate. (more specialized version of parent)
		
		Example 1:  C-type casting
		float a;
		void * b = &a;	//Implicit reinterpretation cast, Accurate type cast to Generic type.
		void * c = (void *) &a;	//Explicit reinterpretation cast

		void * d = &a;	//Implicit promotion is OK
		int * e = d;	//Implicit demotion, HAZARDOUS, wrong value?	// cast Generic type to Accurate type. 
		int * f = (int *) d;	//Explicit demotion is OK

		Example 2: C-type casting
		class Parent				{}
		class Child: public Parent {}

		Child	a;
		Parent *b	= &a;	//implicit 'reinterpretation' cast
		Parent *c	= (Parent*)&a;	//explicit 'reinterpretation' cast

		Parent *d	= &a;	// implicit UPCAST.	OK
							// because you are moving UP the hierarchy
							// i.e. you are treating Child Object as if it were a Parent Object
							// Child Object contains Data from Parent, as well as its own. 
							// Now Parent can safely point to data of its own data members.

		Child * e	= &d;	//implicit DOWNCAST 	NOT OK
							//you are treating a Parent object as if it were a Child Object
							//A Child object has both Parent and Child data, but a Parent object only has the Parent data.
							//so if you didn't know Child object pointer is pointing to a parent, and tried to access memory
							//specific to child, which in this case is not defined, because the parent object it is pointing to 
							//does not have it, you run into undefined behavior.

		Child * e	= (Child*)&d;	//explicit DOWNCAST 	MAY BE NOT OK possible run-time bad consequences
		
• explicit cast
	--------------
		float f = 4; 
		int i = f;	//implicit cast
	
		int i = (int) f;	//explicit cast


• implicit conversions
	----------------------
		- Does CONVERSION
		- Do Upcast
		
		- Does Semantic Check
		- Reliable at Run

		Example:
		int i = 4; 
		double d = i; //implicit conversion. Information is NOT lost assigning 'int' to 'double'

		double D = INT_MAX + 1000;
		int I = D; //implicit conversion. Information is lost. 
				//If you turn on -Wno flag in the compiler, compiler wouldn't allow implicit casting
		i = (int)D; //you instruct compiler that you are explicitly casting.
